<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<number box="[151,163,941,963]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
Forewing with partially overlapped discal hyaline spots (M 
<number box="[816,823,955,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="3.0">3</number>
–CuA 
<number box="[880,887,955,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
and CuA 
<number box="[986,992,955,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
–CuA 
<number box="[1049,1056,955,967]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
), in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[1227,1343,941,963]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[151,1428,183,1079]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,181,1080]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 16. Cumbre species in dorsal and ventral views, male (left) and female (right). 1 – 4, Cumbre cumbre. 5 – 8, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 9 – 12, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. 13 – 16, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286774/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Figs 
<number box="[1279,1343,941,963]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="14.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="13.0">13–16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Species known only from the Andes in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[613,693,973,995]" name="Ecuador" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[870,914,974,995]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Peru</collectingCountry>
at altitudes around 
<quantity box="[1103,1169,973,995]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000m</quantity>
.......... 
<taxonomicName box="[1285,1353,973,995]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Cumbre" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lamasi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1285,1353,973,995]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">lamasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,973,995]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,973,995]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,941,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
- Forewing with non-overlapping discal hyaline spots (M 
<number box="[776,783,1016,1028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="3.0">3</number>
–CuA 
<number box="[840,847,1016,1028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
and CuA 
<number box="[945,951,1016,1028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="1.0">1</number>
–CuA 
<number box="[1008,1015,1016,1028]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
), in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[1185,1287,1003,1025]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[151,1428,183,1079]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,181,1080]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 16. Cumbre species in dorsal and ventral views, male (left) and female (right). 1 – 4, Cumbre cumbre. 5 – 8, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 9 – 12, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. 13 – 16, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286774/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Figs 
<number box="[1236,1287,1003,1025]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="6.5" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="1.0">1–12</number>
</figureCitation>
). Species from 
<collectingCountry box="[225,271,1035,1056]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[281,379,1034,1056]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[388,449,1034,1056]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[458,547,1035,1056]" name="Paraguay" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[594,677,1035,1056]" name="Uruguay" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
.............................................................. 
<number box="[1423,1435,1034,1056]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,941,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<number box="[151,163,1064,1086]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="2.0">2</number>
Hindwing underside with postdiscal spots fused with the submarginal patch (
<figureCitation box="[960,1071,1064,1086]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[151,1428,183,1079]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,181,1080]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 16. Cumbre species in dorsal and ventral views, male (left) and female (right). 1 – 4, Cumbre cumbre. 5 – 8, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 9 – 12, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. 13 – 16, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286774/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Figs 10, 12</figureCitation>
). Species only known from southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[261,305,1094,1115]" name="Peru" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Peru</collectingCountry>
and northwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[483,578,1093,1115]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Argentina</collectingCountry>
........................................................ 
<taxonomicName box="[1262,1352,1093,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Cumbre" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haywardi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1262,1352,1093,1115]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">haywardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1359,1436,1093,1115]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1359,1436,1093,1115]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,941,1320]" box="[151,1436,1122,1144]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<keyLead box="[151,1436,1122,1144]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
- Hindwing underside with postdiscal spots not fused with the submarginal patch (
<figureCitation box="[998,1131,1122,1144]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[151,1428,183,1079]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,181,1080]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 16. Cumbre species in dorsal and ventral views, male (left) and female (right). 1 – 4, Cumbre cumbre. 5 – 8, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 9 – 12, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. 13 – 16, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., holotype and allotype. Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286774/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Figs 2, 4, 6, 8</figureCitation>
)....................... 
<number box="[1424,1436,1122,1144]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="3.0">3</number>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,941,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<number box="[151,163,1152,1174]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="3.0">3</number>
Valva with a disto-dorsal spine at the harpe (
<figureCitation box="[657,730,1152,1174]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 44" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[173,1416,259,1370]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[173,1417,254,1381]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 44. Male genitalia of Cumbre species. Left to right: dorsal view of the tegumen, fenestra and uncus; ventral view of the tegumen, uncus and gnathos; lateral view of the tegumen, uncus, gnathos and saccus; left view of the right valva; ventral view of the inferior fultura and; aedeagus in left, dorsal, ventral and right views (top to bottom). 21 – 26, Cumbre cumbre. 27 – 32, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 33 – 38, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., paratype. 39 – 44, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., paratype. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286776/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[703,730,1152,1174]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
). Lamella postvaginalis distally complete and without a central membranous area; ostium bursae ampule-shaped due to a median narrowing of the lamella postvaginalis (
<figureCitation box="[1160,1232,1181,1203]" captionStart="FIGURES 45 – 52" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1364,1386]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,710,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,700,1343]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 45 – 52. Female genitalia of Cumbre species. Sterigma in lateral and ventral views. 45 and 49, Cumbre cumbre. 46 and 50, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 47 and 51, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., allotype. 48 and 52, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., allotype. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286777/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[1205,1232,1181,1203]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="49.0">49</number>
</figureCitation>
). Species widely distributed along the eastern Brazilian region, from Bahia to Rio Grande do Sul in areas above 
<quantity box="[1108,1162,1210,1232]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="500.0">500m</quantity>
(fig 
<number box="[1209,1234,1210,1232]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="61.0">61</number>
).......... 
<taxonomicName box="[1364,1435,1210,1232]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Phanis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cumbre">
<emphasis box="[1364,1435,1210,1232]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">cumbre</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,941,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
<keyLead pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
- Valva without a disto-dorsal spine at the harpe (
<figureCitation box="[688,760,1240,1262]" captionStart="FIGURES 21 – 44" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1403,1425]" captionTargetBox="[173,1416,259,1370]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[173,1417,254,1381]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 21 – 44. Male genitalia of Cumbre species. Left to right: dorsal view of the tegumen, fenestra and uncus; ventral view of the tegumen, uncus and gnathos; lateral view of the tegumen, uncus, gnathos and saccus; left view of the right valva; ventral view of the inferior fultura and; aedeagus in left, dorsal, ventral and right views (top to bottom). 21 – 26, Cumbre cumbre. 27 – 32, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 33 – 38, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., paratype. 39 – 44, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., paratype. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286776/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[733,760,1240,1262]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="30.0">30</number>
</figureCitation>
). Lamella postvaginalis disjunct and with a central membranous area; ostium bursae subquadrangular (
<figureCitation box="[536,607,1269,1291]" captionStart="FIGURES 45 – 52" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1364,1386]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,710,1342]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,700,1343]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 45 – 52. Female genitalia of Cumbre species. Sterigma in lateral and ventral views. 45 and 49, Cumbre cumbre. 46 and 50, Cumbre meridionalis stat. rev.. 47 and 51, Cumbre haywardi sp. nov., allotype. 48 and 52, Cumbre lamasi sp. nov., allotype. Scale bar = 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286777/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[580,607,1269,1291]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="50.0">50</number>
</figureCitation>
). Species distributed throughout southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1047,1108,1269,1291]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1117,1207,1270,1291]" name="Paraguay" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1340,1435,1269,1291]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Argentina</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[265,349,1299,1320]" name="Uruguay" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
in lowland deciduous forest below 
<quantity box="[691,758,1298,1320]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" unit="m" value="1000.0">1000m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[771,840,1298,1320]" captionStart="FIGURE 61" captionStartId="15.[151,250,967,989]" captionTargetBox="[159,1435,195,943]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,195,943]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 61. Geographical distribution of Cumbre species.? = Record of C. meridionalis for Uruguay according to Biezanko &amp; Ruffinelli (1962)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/286779/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="50">
Fig. 
<number box="[816,840,1298,1320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="50" value="61.0">61</number>
</figureCitation>
)............................... 
